{
  "answer": "**No such passage exists in the work.** \n\nVairocana (a form of the Buddha, preaching in the Monastery of Enlightenment) instructs the *rākṣasa* ascetic Kuñjarakarṇa to travel to Yama's realm specifically to *witness* the sufferings of sinners firsthand, as a prelude to further teaching on *dharma* and karma.[^1] He does not describe the hells (*narakas*) himself. Instead:\n\n- The graphic depictions of torments (e.g., the City of the Iron Earth, sword-trees and sword-grass, iron mountains crushing sinners, impaling on stakes, fire-mouthed *rākṣasas*, etc.) occur during Kuñjarakarṇa's narrated journey to Yama.[^2]\n- Yama later briefly outlines the punishments (e.g., boiling in the Gomukha cauldron for 100,000 years, tearing by weapon-birds, burning under bamboo poles) and explains their karmic causes.[^3]\n\nVairocana's own speeches focus on non-duality, the five souls (*ātmans*), debts to gods/parents/teachers/world, unity of Buddhist/Śaiva/Vaiṣṇava deities, and paths to *mokṣa*, without detailing hellish realms.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-f907b3).\n\n[^2]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, ch. 1 [paragraphs](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-4f1644)–[p-8051c0) (journey and torments).\n\n[^3]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, ch. 1 [paragraphs](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-cf696c)–[p-2efb11).\n\n[^4]: *Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana*, ch. 1 [paragraphs](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-7241a0), [p-6c6127), [p-e871d0)–[p-6c6127).",
